# Multilingual Considerations — {Agent Name}

## Scope per channel

Per `projects/{p}/project.config.yaml multilingual`:

| Channel | Multilingual support | Default language | Supported languages |
|---|---|---|---|
| crm | per project.config | per project.config | per project.config |
| portal | per project.config | per project.config | per project.config |
| canvas | per project.config | per project.config | per project.config |
| reports | per project.config | per project.config | per project.config |

This agent's relevant channels: list which channels apply to this agent's work products (e.g., CE owns crm + portal + canvas; reporting owns reports; F&O has its own label translation system).

## Translation approach per artefact type

For each artefact type this agent produces, document how labels and content are localised. Common patterns:

- **Resource files / .resx** — for plugin error messages, label tables
- **Translation table entities** — entity-based localisation
- **Localised solution components** — per-locale solution variants
- **Power BI dataset translations** — built-in PBI translation framework
- **Liquid template fragments** — for portal multilingual pages

## What's NOT translated

- Section IDs (`FR-01`, `TS-03`) — always English
- Stable code identifiers (entity names, field schema names)
- Comments in code

## Verification

When `multilingual.{channel}: true`, the test plan must include a "Multilingual" suite covering label rendering in non-default languages, RTL support (where applicable), and locale-specific number/date formatting.
